    <section class="hero">
        <h1>The Importance of Marine Ecosystems</h1>
        <p>Oceans cover more than 70% of Earth's surface and are essential to life. They regulate the climate, provide food and resources, and support global biodiversity.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="content" id="importance">
        <div class="section">
            <h2>Importance of Marine Ecosystems</h2>
            <p>Marine ecosystems offer numerous benefits crucial for the health of our planet and future generations.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Economic Value:</strong> Marine ecosystems contribute billions to global economies through fisheries, tourism, and other industries.</li>
                <li><strong>Climate Regulation:</strong> Oceans absorb carbon dioxide, mitigating climate change and maintaining temperature stability.</li>
                <li><strong>Biodiversity Hotspot:</strong> They house countless species, many yet undiscovered, supporting ecological balance.</li>
                <li><strong>Oxygen Production:</strong> Phytoplankton produce a significant portion of the oxygen we breathe.</li>
                <li><strong>Recreation and Culture:</strong> Oceans inspire art, recreation, and cultural heritage around the world.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="section" id="threats">
            <h2>Threats to Marine Ecosystems</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Overfishing:</strong> Harvesting fish at unsustainable rates leads to depleted stocks and affects food security.</li>
                <li><strong>Pollution:</strong> Plastic waste, chemicals, and runoff harm marine life and contaminate ecosystems.</li>
                <li><strong>Climate Change:</strong> Rising temperatures and acidification impact marine habitats, biodiversity, and fisheries.</li>
                <li><strong>Habitat Destruction:</strong> Coastal development and bottom trawling damage vital marine habitats.</li>
                <li><strong>Invasive Species:</strong> Non-native species disrupt local ecosystems, endangering native marine life.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="section" id="sdg14">
            <h2>Sustainable Development Goal 14</h2>
            <p>SDG 14, adopted by the UN, emphasizes conserving oceans and sustainably using marine resources for development.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Conservation:</strong> Protect marine populations by reducing overfishing and destructive practices.</li>
                <li><strong>Pollution Control:</strong> Minimize pollution from plastics and runoff to preserve water quality.</li>
                <li><strong>Climate Action:</strong> Address the impacts of ocean warming, acidification, and sea-level rise.</li>
                <li><strong>Sustainable Management:</strong> Promote responsible use of fisheries and protect marine resources.</li>
                <li><strong>Marine Education:</strong> Raise awareness on ocean conservation to foster global stewardship.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Challenges in Implementing SDG 14</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Funding Constraints:</strong> Conservation and monitoring require substantial resources.</li>
                <li><strong>Enforcement Issues:</strong> Implementing regulations is challenging and requires international cooperation.</li>
                <li><strong>Competing Interests:</strong> Balancing needs of different stakeholders can complicate conservation efforts.</li>
                <li><strong>Lack of Awareness:</strong> Limited public understanding can hinder conservation progress.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <footer id="conclusion">
        <h2>Conclusion and Call to Action</h2>
        <p>Protecting marine ecosystems is essential for the health of our planet. By acting together, we can address the challenges facing our oceans and ensure a sustainable future for generations to come.</p>
